            <li><strong>Cheerful Levels:</strong> Playful level design with a lighter tone that feels less intimidating</li>
            <li><strong>Upbeat Soundtrack:</strong> Catchy, energetic music that's fun and engaging throughout</li>
            <li><strong>Playful Obstacles:</strong> Creative and colorful obstacle designs that are visually appealing</li>
            <li><strong>Smooth Controls:</strong> The responsive one-button gameplay you love from the original</li>
            <li><strong>Welcoming Atmosphere:</strong> An overall aesthetic that welcomes players of all skill levels</li>
          </ul>
          
          <h2 id="gameplay-mechanics">Gameplay Mechanics</h2>
          <p>Geometry Dash Breeze uses the same simple control system as the original. Press spacebar, click the mouse, or tap the screen to jump. Your character moves automatically forward, and you need to time your jumps perfectly to avoid obstacles and complete each level. The fundamental mechanics are familiar, but the new level designs provide fresh challenges.</p>
          
          <h2 id="level-design">Level Design and Difficulty</h2>
          <p>The levels in Breeze are designed to be fun and engaging while maintaining a good difficulty curve. Early levels are accessible for beginners, while later levels provide solid challenges for experienced players. The colorful aesthetic makes the game feel less intimidating than the original, making it more appealing to casual players.</p>
          
          <h2 id="game-modes">Game Modes and Character Forms</h2>
          <p>Like other Geometry Dash games, Breeze features multiple game modes with different character forms. Your cube transforms into a ship, ball, UFO, wave, and more. Each form has unique physics and controls, keeping the gameplay varied and interesting throughout your journey. Learning how each form works is essential for progression.</p>
          
          <h2 id="cube-form">The Cube Form in Breeze</h2>
          <p>The cube is your default form and the most straightforward to control. In Breeze, the cube form is used extensively in the early and mid-game levels, making it essential to master for progression.</p>
          
